By variable sized array do you mean e.g.
```
int size = ...;
float my_array[size];
```
?

Note that this is not actually part of the C++ standard (AFAIK), but it just a popular extension that popular compilers have implemented. Since this code will only be compiled on Apple platforms, it may be okay if it compiles now given our current toolchain, but I think you may as well stick with heap allocations, given that you need one anyway to store _filterBanks from initializer to calls to `apply`. 

FWIW, I think it's fairly standard to have e.g.
```
NSData *lowerBankData = [[NSData alloc] initWithLength:spectrumSize*sizeof(float)];
float* lowerBank = (float*)lowerBankData.mutableBytes;
```
Then Objective C will take care of memory management for you, acknowledging that the `lowerBank` pointer will only remain valid as long as `lowerBankData` is around.

