```
def _support_1d(func):
    R"""Decorator for class methods that accept one dimensional input or
    two dimensional input for the first argument.
    """
    @wraps(func)
    def wrapper(self, *args, **kwargs):
        if len(args):
            args1 = args[0]
        else:
            args1 = next(iter(kwargs))
        arg1 = np.asarray(arg1)
        if len(arg1.shape) == 1:
            flat = True
            arg1 = np.atleast_2d(arg1)
        else:
            flat = False

        ret = func(self, arg1)
        if flat:
            return ret.squeeze()
        else:
            return ret
    return wrapper
```
is the only way I can think of to handle that case.

> Is this just to optimize the payload size a bit?

Right. It's not really a problem, it's just a little unfortunate that every single value ends up as an output value. In any case, I went ahead and added a commit that avoids emitting an output value when it's not needed.

More problematic: I've found that in the .NET SDK `Input<T>` (and `InputList<T>`, `InputMap<V>`, and `InputUnion<T0, T1>`) eagerly stores the value of `T` as an `Output<T>`:

https://github.com/pulumi/pulumi/blob/0a38bc295cfc5ae3c325dcece169da5a5e80fffc/sdk/dotnet/Pulumi/Core/Input.cs#L22-L31

So a test like this fails:

```csharp
[Fact]
public static Task TestSecretInInputList()
    => RunInNormal(async () =>
    {
        var input = new InputList<string>{ Output.CreateSecret("hello") };
        var expected = ImmutableArray<object>.Empty.Add(
            ImmutableDictionary<string, object>.Empty
                .Add(Constants.SpecialSigKey, Constants.SpecialOutputValueSig)
                .Add("value", "hello")
                .Add("secret", true));

        var s = new Serializer(excessiveDebugOutput: false);
        var actual = await s.SerializeAsync("", input, keepResources: true, keepOutputValues: true);

        Assert.Equal(expected, actual!);
    });
```

I'm expecting the serialized value to look like (the value inside the list is an output value):

```json
[
    {
        "4dabf18193072939515e22adb298388d": "d0e6a833031e9bbcd3f4e8bde6ca49a4",
        "value": "hello",
        "secret": true
    }
]
```

But actually getting (the top-level value is an output value):

```json
{
    "4dabf18193072939515e22adb298388d": "d0e6a833031e9bbcd3f4e8bde6ca49a4",
    "value": ["hello"],
    "secret": true
}
```

Which basically defeats the purpose of why we added output values to begin with.

It turns out that regular .NET programs (that aren't even using MLCs) end up having undesirable previews because of this behavior with `Input<T>`. For example:

```csharp
using Pulumi;
using Pulumi.Random;
using Pulumi.Aws.S3;

class MyStack : Stack
{
    public MyStack()
    {
        var randString = new RandomString("str", new RandomStringArgs { Length = 10 });
        var bucket = new Bucket("bucket", new BucketArgs {
            Tags = {
                { "hello", "world" },
                { "hi", "there" },
                { "foo", randString.Id },
            }
        });
    }
}
```

Has the following preview diff:

```
        tags        : output<string>
```

When we want it to be like this:

```
        tags        : {
            hello     : "world"
            hi        : "there"
            foo       : output<string>
        }

```

My suggestion is we merge this PR as-is (modulo addressing any review feedback) and open an issue to track this issue with `Input<T>` eagerly converting values to `Output<T>`. And fix that separately. I'm thinking the fix will involve just avoiding/deferring the eager `Output<T>` conversion as much as possible, and only do it when needed.

